<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06092093 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06092093 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  ROMANIA; GOVERNMENT; INCREASE; FOOD; COST  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Panicky shoppers emptied state stores as the government prepared to more thandouble basic food prices today. The move is meant to help the economy, butcritics say it will deepen poverty and misery.;    In the days before theincreases, Romanians snapped up chickens, bread, sugar and anything else thatwas for sale. Only bread and milk stores were open Sunday, and only briefly.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  General News  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  ROMANIANS PANIC, STRIP STORES OF FOOD  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The government hopes the price reforms -- along with parallel salaryincreases and a currency devaluation -- will breathe some life into othersectors of the economy, including Romania's moribund heavy industry.;   Reforms were required by the International Monetary Fund in exchange for a $1billion aid package to Romania, which is expected to receive final approvalFriday.;    But the National Salvation Front government has come under abarrage of criticism from trade unions, opposition parties and dissidentswithin the government.;    Three prominent opposition parties -- the NationalLiberal Party, the National Peasant Party and the Ecologist Party -- calledlast week for a delay in the price increases, saying they will reduce theliving standard to &quot;the limits of poverty and desperation.&quot;;    Romaniaalready has one of the lowest standards of living in Europe, a legacy ofdecades of Communist rule.;    Emil Tokacs, a Liberal Party senator, calledthe move &quot;not a price liberalization, but merely a price hike.&quot;;    Unions saythe increases are premature because producers are still state-owned and itwill be a long time before there is real competition among them.;    Theincreases are the second phase of a policy intended to bring prices in linewith products' real market value and pave the way for a market economy.;   The first phase, which took effect Nov. 1, doubled and tripled the cost ofalmost everything except energy, food and essential services, which remainedprotected.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Bucharest, Romania  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910401  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Monday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.COL>  4D  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  299  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Monday April 1, 199100092093,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>